full_text: The account file provides a complete view of the account, where you can view and edit account information. Locate the account. Select Write Construction as an example. The Account Summary Dashboard provides several information panels that are important to customer service representatives, agents, and underwriters. It contains details about the account holder, a general overview of the account, current activities, a list of policy terms, open policy transactions for the account. Claims, billing details, producers, related accounts, and notes are also on the account summary page. By default, it only lists the top three entries for many items. To view more items, go to their individual screens. The menu links in the left sidebar provide supporting information for the account. This menu is context sensitive. Go to the contacts screen. A contact setup from the account file can be used by all policies within the account. One contact can play multiple roles on the account and policy. Some contact information is shared across policies, while some revisioned at policy level, depending on the configuration. In this setup, Write Construction has two roles as a contact, account holder and named insured. Contacts can be edited by clicking the edit icon. Click cancel to go back. Clicking the view icon takes you to the contact file. Go back to the account. Go to the location screen. When an account is created, the account holder's address is the primary location by default, but it can be changed if needed. Locations are legally enforced on the policies, but Policy Center stores locations at the account level for easier location maintenance. Locations created for a policy are added at the account level automatically. You can add a new location for the account. A new location can be specific or nonspecific. Select nonspecific location. Locations are required to be added at the location location if a particular address is unknown. Select the state. Save the location information. Clicking the link on fields like the location number opens the location details screen for editing. Editing a location is only for correction purposes or updates. Certain fields cannot be changed during edits, including nonspecific location, state and country. Corrections and updates propagate to newly created policy transactions, but does not affect enforced policies. Save the changes. Save the changes. Go to the participants screen. A participant is a Policy Center user who is assigned to an account with a specific role. Participants include creators, underwriters, producers, and auditors, etc. They can be used to assign an activity related on the account. Click Edit to manage the participants. Add a participant. Add a participant.  Click the role drop-down. These are the out-of-the-box examples for roles. Let's select Auditor. Click Select User. Enter the user. Enter the search criteria. Search for the user. Select the user. Select the assigned group. Save the participant information. Go to the Policy Transactions screen. This screen lists all of the policy transactions on the account. They can be filtered by status, type, and product. The status filters are all open and complete. You can filter by all of the policy transaction types. Go to the Submission Manager screen. In the Submission Manager, all policy-related submissions appear for easy access. There are some quick action buttons. Go to the Underwriting Files screen. Underwriting files allow users to view risk information by group. The base configuration puts submissions in one group and all renewals in another group. Click the Submission group. You can view the details of this submission group. Click up to Underwriting Files to go back. Go to Related Accounts. You can view, add, and remove related accounts. Click Add. You must select a relationship. It indicates the account relationship. We'll just cancel out of it. You can also search for accounts with a common account holder or named Insured. Go to the Documents screen. You can search for and view any attached documents related to the account or policies in the account. You can attach documents to the account. All documents attached to policies are also visible at the account level. Go to the Notes screen. A note is a detailed record of the actions or thought processes of a Policy Center user. You can search for, view and edit the notes. Go to Claims. If Policy Center is integrated with the Claims system, the claim information about the account is displayed on the Claims screen. You can search for claims by policies, jobs, or dates. Go to the Billing screen. Similarly, if the billing system is integrated, it displays billing information on the Billing screen. For example, the past due amount for each policy term in Invoices. The Policy Terms tab at the bottom of the screen displays summary information for individual policy terms. You can see policies falling under this account as well as policies that are billed to this account. Go to the Invoices tab. The Invoices tab displays invoices retrieved from the billing system. You can choose to display invoices for the last 3, 6, and 12 months. These are the sample data for account billing. Go to the History screen. The History screen gives the user an overview of all the transactions related to the account and policies in the account. You can filter the history events by user, timestamp or the Related to field. Scroll down. Select the Policy for Business Owners. Click Search. It returns the history for the Business Owners policy. This is the end of demonstration for the supporting account information.
